  "prompt": "Can I write improvements with supplementary exams in intermediate 1 year?",
  "response": "Yes, you can generally write improvements (reappear for exams) with supplementary exams after your Intermediate 1st year. Here\u2019s how it typically works:\n\n1. **Supplementary Exams**: These are special exams conducted for students who fail one or more subjects in their regular exams. If you didn\u2019t pass certain subjects in your Intermediate 1st year, you can reappear for those subjects in the supplementary exams.\n\n2. **Improvement Exams**: Some education boards also allow students to write improvement exams for subjects they have already passed but want to score higher marks. This is usually offered in the next academic year or during supplementary exam sessions.\n\n3. **Check Your Board\u2019s Rules**: The exact process and rules for supplementary and improvement exams vary by education board (e.g., CBSE, State Boards). You should check your board\u2019s official notification or contact your school/college for specific guidelines.\n\n4. **Limitations**: Some boards may impose certain conditions, such as a limit on the number of times you can attempt supplementary exams or a cap on the maximum marks you can achieve in improvement exams.\n\n5. **Next Steps**: If you\u2019re planning to write improvements, make sure to register for the supplementary exams within the specified deadline and prepare thoroughly.\n\nAlways verify the latest rules from your board or institution, as policies can change. Good luck!",
